[src:emberjs/ember-js] Ember is used on websites including HashiCorp, DigitalOcean, Apple Music, Square, Inc., Intercom, Discourse, Groupon, LinkedIn, Live Nation, Ghost, Nordstrom, and Twitch.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Although primarily considered a framework for the web, it is also possible to build desktop and mobile applications with Ember when utilizing a hybrid app pattern.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] The most notable example of an Ember desktop application is Apple Music, a feature of the iTunes desktop application.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] The Ember trademark is owned by Tilde Inc.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] In December 2011, the SproutCore 2.0 framework was renamed to Ember.js, to reduce confusion between the application framework and the widget library of SproutCore 1.0.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] The framework was created by Yehuda Katz who was a member of the jQuery, Ruby on Rails and SproutCore core teams.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Ember sets out to provide a solution to the client-side application problem.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Ember is one component of a set of tools to provide a development stack.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Ember CLI provides an application structure and build pipeline with an add-on.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Ember aims to prioritize backward compatibility and allow it to be maintained while still evolving the framework.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Yehuda Katz, one of Ember's co-founders, is a member on TC39, which is the committee responsible for future versions of the JavaScript language.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Like Ruby on Rails, Ember follows *convention over configuration* (CoC), and the *don't repeat yourself* (DRY) principle.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] It has been described as a highly opinionated framework built to be very flexible.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] In Ember, the state of an application is represented by a URL.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Each URL has a corresponding "route object" that controls what is visible to the user.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Every route has an associated model, containing the data associated with the current state of the application.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] objects from a server and use those objects as models, most applications use a model library such as Ember Data to handle this.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Its behavior is implemented using JavaScript, and its appearance is defined using HTMLBars templates.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] They can also be nested and can communicate with their parent components through actions (events).
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Other component libraries, such as Polymer can also be used with Ember.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Services are just singleton objects to hold long-lived data such as user sessions.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Ember.js is one component of a complete front-end stack built and supported by the Ember core team.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Ember-CLI aims to bring convention over configuration to build tools.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] A command line utility based on broccoli, running the command `ember new <app-name>` generates a new Ember app with the default stack.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Most Ember applications use Ember Data, a data-persistence library providing many of the facilities of object-relational mapping (ORM).
[src:emberjs/ember-js] However it is also possible to use Ember without Ember Data.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Ember Data maps client-side models to server-side data.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] It can then load and save records and their relationships without any configuration via a RESTful JSON API that implements the JSON API specification, provided certain conventions are followed.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] However it is also configurable and can work with servers through the use of adapters and addons.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] JSON API has server library implementations for PHP, Node.js, Ruby, Python, Go, .NET and Java.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Connecting to a Java-Spring-based server is also documented.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] The first stable version of Ember Data (labeled 1.13 to align with Ember itself) was released on June 18 June 2015.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] The Ember Inspector is an extension currently available for the Mozilla Firefox and Google Chrome web browsers for debugging Ember applications.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Features include the ability to see which templates, components, and views are currently rendered, see the properties of any Ember object with a UI that computes bindings and computed properties, and access one's application's objects from the console.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] If Ember Data is used, one can also see the records loaded for each model.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Fastboot is an Ember CLI add-on created by the Ember core team that gives Ember developers the ability to run their apps in Node.js.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] This feature allows end users to see HTML and CSS right away, with JavaScript downloading in the background and taking over once it has fully loaded.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Liquid Fire provides animation support for Ember applications.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Features include animated transitions between routes and between models within a single route.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] It provides a DSL for solidifying spatial route relationships, cleanly separated from view-layer implementation details.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] An example would be to animate a screen transition so that the new screen appears to slide in from one edge of the browser.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] See the releases blog for the full list of releases and detailed changelog.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Ember follows a six-week release cycle, inspired by the rapid release cycle of Google Chrome.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Starting with Ember 2.0, related projects supported by the core team have their releases coordinated, and share a version number with Ember itself.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Ember follows the semantic versioning convention.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] In particular, breaking changes are only introduced at significant version numbers, such as 1.0, 2.0, etc.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] While new features can be added at point releases (1.1, 1.2...), and features deprecated, no breaking changes to the public APIs are introduced.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Tooling was also under development in 2015 to help streamline the upgrade process.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] The process follows the core Ember principle of Stability without Stagnation and is in marked contrast to the upgrade plans of similar projects such as AngularJS.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Project status can be tracked via the core team meeting minutes.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] However, major changes to Ember go through the Request For Comment process.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] This gives the Ember community a chance to give feedback on new proposals.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] Unlike other projects such as AngularJS (Google) and React (Facebook) which have the backing of one main company, Ember.js has a variety of sponsors and backers.
[src:emberjs/ember-js] These include users of the framework such as Yahoo!, LinkedIn and Bustle.
[src:emberjs/frameworks-libraries] JavaScript frameworks are an essential part of modern front-end web development, providing developers with tried and tested tools for building scalable, interactive web applications.
[src:emberjs/frameworks-libraries] Many modern companies use frameworks as a standard part of their tooling, so many front-end development jobs now require framework experience.
